emale":"1242–Overleden","1357":"1357","1202":"1202","1279":"1279","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","about 1330":"circa 1330","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","1280":"1280","Eccles, Lancashire, England":"Eccles, Lancashire, England","Notton Royston West Riding Yorkshire":"Notton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1275–1357":"1275–1357","1276–1350":"1276–1350","1279–Female":"1279–Deceased","1280–1307":"1280–1307","–Female":"Deceased","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1202–1275":"1202–1275","1242–Female":"1242–Deceased","1357":"1357","1202":"1202","1279":"1279","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","about 1330":"about 1330","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","1280":"1280","Eccles, Lancashire, England":"Eccles, Lancashire, England","Notton Royston West Riding Yorkshire":"Notton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called with Old English <i>bere</i> or <i>bær</i> ‘barley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, i.e. an outlying grange. Compare   Barwick  . The name is also found in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Bartún</b>.","Polish (<b>Bartoń</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Bartoň</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bartłomiej</i>, Czech <i>Bartoloměj</i>, Slovak <i>Bartolomej</i>, from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Notton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton in Lacock (Wilts) or Notton in Maiden Newton (Dorset), both of which are recorded as  <i>Natton</i> and  <i>Netton</i> in the 13th century. The place-names derive from Old English  <i>nēat</i> ‘cattle’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Noton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Natton","meanings":["English: variant of both   Notton   and   Noton  ."]},{"name":"Noton","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Notone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Nocton</i> in 1230. The place-name derives from Old English  <i>hnoc</i> ‘wether sheep’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Notton  , and perhaps also with   Knutton   and   Nocton  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Gilbert de Barton de Notton was born in 1275, in Notton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Gilbert de Barton de Notton,, was 74 and his mother, Margery Eland, was 34. He married Bettye Cecilla de Barton de Notton. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1357, at the age of 82."},"et":{"1275–1357":"1275–1357","1276–1350":"1276–1350","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","1280–1307":"1280–1307","–Female":"Surnud","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1202–1275":"1202–1275","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","1357":"1357","1202":"1202","1279":"1279","1276":"1276","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","1280":"1280","Eccles, Lancashire, England":"Eccles, Lancashire, England","Notton Royston West Riding Yorkshire":"Notton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1275–1357":"1275–1357","1276–1350":"1276–1350","1279–Female":"1279–Kuollut","1280–1307":"1280–1307","–Female":"Kuollut","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1